{"metadata":{"modules":[{"name":"Brunow"}],"color":{"standardColorIdentifier":"purple"},"title":"Constantly Researching","platforms":[{"introducedAt":"2017.01.20","name":"Brunow"}]},"kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"date: 2016-04-14T07:22:28-05:00"}],"sections":[],"schemaVersion":{"patch":0,"minor":3,"major":0},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/Brunow\/documentation\/Brunow","doc:\/\/Brunow\/documentation\/Brunow\/Archive","doc:\/\/Brunow\/documentation\/Brunow\/2016"]]},"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/Brunow\/documentation\/Brunow\/04-14-constantly-researching"},"topicSectionsStyle":"detailedGrid","primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"I think you can learn a lot by asking “why” in everyday conversations. I don’t think that most people think about the why of what they’re doing, what they like, or the things they choose.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"You probably won’t get to any “truth” by asking why. You’ll learn more about the person than the problem, but that’s OK.","type":"text"}]}]}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/brunow\/04-14-constantly-researching"]}],"references":{"doc://Brunow/documentation/Brunow/Archive":{"type":"topic","kind":"article","role":"collectionGroup","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"All posts"}],"title":"Archive","identifier":"doc:\/\/Brunow\/documentation\/Brunow\/Archive","url":"\/documentation\/brunow\/archive"},"doc://Brunow/documentation/Brunow/2016":{"type":"topic","kind":"article","role":"collectionGroup","abstract":[],"title":"2016","identifier":"doc:\/\/Brunow\/documentation\/Brunow\/2016","url":"\/documentation\/brunow\/2016"},"doc://Brunow/documentation/Brunow":{"type":"topic","role":"collection","title":"Brunow","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"text":"David Brunow, known as Brunow [ˈbɹunoʊ] to the folks he works with, is a human living on Earth. Yo